008/**
009 * Provides access to a precalculated, tiling plane of 2D blue noise, that is, noise without high-frequency components,
010 * as well as seeded modifications to that tiling blue noise plane that make it have even fewer patterns.
011 * Not actually a noise class like {@link FastNoise}. The blue-noise distribution has the practical effect that a value
012 * only appears next to a similar value very rarely. For a quick introduction, see
013 * <a href="https://blog.demofox.org/2018/01/30/what-the-heck-is-blue-noise/">Alan Wolfe's blog</a>, which has many more
014 * useful posts and links that often relate to blue noise and its relatives, like low-discrepancy sequences (which
015 * SquidLib calls quasi-random sequences, like {@link VanDerCorputQRNG}).
016 * <br>
017 * This uses 64x64 grayscale textures 0 through 63 from <a href="http://momentsingraphics.de/BlueNoise.html">Christoph
018 * Peters' invaluable blue noise resource</a>. It may use more of the textures from that site in the future.
019 * <br>
020 * Created by Tommy Ettinger on 10/15/2019.
021 */
022public class BlueNoise {
023    private BlueNoise() {
024    }
025
026    /**
027     * Raw data this class uses, as 64 1D byte arrays. Any of the 1D arrays this holds can be passed to
028     * {@link #get(int, int, byte[])} or {@link #getSeededScratchy(int, int, int, byte[])} as their noiseData parameter. This
029     * group of byte arrays is static, which is probably OK even on Android as long as no one writes to it, and uses
030     * {@link StandardCharsets} to decode itself from a String, which only works on GWT 2.8.2 and newer.
031     * Each byte array can be considered [x][y] indexed or [y][x] indexed; the original images were [y][x] indexed.
032     */

120    /**
121     * The raw data this class uses, as a 1D byte array. You probably don't want to use this field, but you might, so it
122     * is public... but don't write to it. It's static, which is probably OK even on Android as long as no one changes
123     * it, and uses {@link StandardCharsets} to decode itself from a String, which only works on GWT 2.8.2 and newer.
124     * This can be considered [x][y] indexed or [y][x] indexed; the original image was [y][x] indexed.
125     */
126    public static final byte[] RAW_NOISE = ALT_NOISE[0];
127
128    /**
129     * Stores the same values as {@link #RAW_NOISE} if considered [x][y] indexed; available for convenient usage by
130     * GreasedRegion and other classes that can use 2D byte arrays.
131     */
132    public static final byte[][] RAW_2D = new byte[64][64];

134    /**
135     * A 256-element array of {@link GreasedRegion}s, each 64x64, where the first GreasedRegion has an impossibly strict
136     * threshold on what points to include (it is empty), but the second has some points far apart, the third has more,
137     * and so on until the last element includes almost all points.
138     */
139    public static final GreasedRegion[] LEVELS = new GreasedRegion[256];
140
141    static {
142        for (int x = 0; x < 64; x++) {
143            System.arraycopy(RAW_NOISE, x << 6, RAW_2D[x], 0, 64);
144        }
145        LEVELS[0] = new GreasedRegion(64, 64);
146        for (int i = -127; i < 128; i++) {
147            LEVELS[i + 128] = new GreasedRegion(RAW_2D, -128, i);
148        }
149    }

151    /**
152     * Gets a byte from the raw data this stores, treating it as an infinite 2D plane of tiling 64x64 regions. You can
153     * interpret the blue noise in many ways, but it is meant to be used with a threshold to select mostly widely-spaced
154     * points when the threshold requires values greater than 100 or less than -100, or irregularly-shaped patterns of
155     * points when the threshold is in the middle, like for values less than 0.
156     *
157     * @param x x position, can be any int; results will repeat every 64 cells
158     * @param y y position, can be any int; results will repeat every 64 cells
159     * @return a byte that obeys a blue-noise distribution, so a value is only next to a similar value very rarely
160     */
161    public static byte get(final int x, final int y) {
162        return RAW_NOISE[(y << 6 & 0xFC0) | (x & 0x3F)];
163    }

165    /**
166     * Gets a byte from some raw data at least 4096 bytes in length, treating it as an infinite 2D plane
167     * of tiling 64x64 regions. You probably want to get the noiseData from an element of {@link #ALT_NOISE}.
168     *
169     * @param x         x position, can be any int; results will repeat every 64 cells
170     * @param y         y position, can be any int; results will repeat every 64 cells
171     * @param noiseData a byte array with minimum length 4096; probably from {@link #ALT_NOISE}
172     * @return a byte that obeys a blue-noise distribution, so a value is only next to a similar value very rarely
173     */
174    public static byte get(final int x, final int y, final byte[] noiseData) {
175        return noiseData[(y << 6 & 0xFC0) | (x & 0x3F)];
176    }

178    /**
179     * Gets a modified byte from the raw data this stores, using seed to adjust repeated sections of blue noise so
180     * patterns are much less noticeable. Unlike {@link #get(int, int)}, this won't repeat every 64 cells on x or y, but
181     * it isn't as correct at matching blue-noise frequencies, and tends to look "scratchy" in places, like TV static.
182     *
183     * @param x    x position, can be any int; results will not repeat for a very long time
184     * @param y    y position, can be any int; results will not repeat for a very long time
185     * @param seed seed value, can be any int; should be the same for all calls that should be from the same 2D plane
186     * @return a byte that obeys an almost-blue-noise distribution, so a value is only next to a similar value rarely
187     */
188    public static byte getSeededScratchy(final int x, final int y, int seed) {
189        seed ^= (x >>> 5) * 0x1827F5 ^ (y >>> 5) * 0x123C21;
190        return (byte) (RAW_NOISE[(y << 6 & 0xFC0) | (x & 0x3F)] ^
191                ((seed ^ (seed << 19 | seed >>> 13) ^ (seed << 5 | seed >>> 27) ^ 0xD1B54A35) * 0x125493 >>> 26)
192                ^ (x + x + y >> 2 & 0x3F) ^ (x - y - y >> 2 & 0x3F));
193    }

195    /**
196     * Gets a modified byte from some raw noise data in an array of at least 4096 bytes, using seed to adjust repeated
197     * sections of noise so patterns are much less noticeable. Unlike {@link #get(int, int)}, this won't repeat every 64
198     * cells on x or y, but it isn't as correct at matching blue-noise frequencies, and tends to look "scratchy" in
199     * places, like TV static. You probably want to get the noiseData from an element of {@link #ALT_NOISE}.
200     *
201     * @param x         x position, can be any int; results will not repeat for a very long time
202     * @param y         y position, can be any int; results will not repeat for a very long time
203     * @param seed      seed value, can be any int; should be the same for all calls that should be from the same 2D plane
204     * @param noiseData a byte array with minimum length 4096; probably from {@link #ALT_NOISE}
205     * @return a byte that obeys an almost-blue-noise distribution, so a value is only next to a similar value rarely
206     */
207    public static byte getSeededScratchy(final int x, final int y, int seed, final byte[] noiseData) {
208        seed ^= (x >>> 5) * 0x1827F5 ^ (y >>> 5) * 0x123C21;
209        return (byte) (noiseData[(y << 6 & 0xFC0) | (x & 0x3F)] ^
210                ((seed ^ (seed << 19 | seed >>> 13) ^ (seed << 5 | seed >>> 27) ^ 0xD1B54A35) * 0x125493 >>> 26)
211                ^ (x + x + y >> 2 & 0x3F) ^ (x - y - y >> 2 & 0x3F));
212    }

216     * can almost-seamlessly tile the plane non-periodically. The 16 textures are each 64 by 64 cells, so if you give
217     * this x and y that are always between 0 and 63 inclusive, it will only choose from one texture. Otherwise, it will
218     * probably sample from two, chosen so that there is the least-noticeable edge between the two. Sometimes edges or
219     * corners are visible, but this isn't too serious, especially if you use thresholds to get only points above or
220     * below some value.

223     * code that generated this blue noise is almost entirely Alan Wolfe's work, with some small changes for the "sigma"
224     * (effectively, how coarse small clusters of similar pixels are allowed to be) and just as importantly, for the
225     * initial pattern that is filled in to create blue noise (normal generation uses low-density white noise as a
226     * basis, but this used arranged and repeated chunks of two different Halton sequences, which already have
227     * blue-noise-like properties).

229     * @param y         y position, can be any int; results will not repeat for a very long time
230     * @param seed      seed value, can be any int; should be the same for all calls that should be from the same 2D plane

256    /**
257     * Generates a 2D int array (as with {@code new int[width][height]}) and fills it with the (seeded variant) blue
258     * noise of this class, finding any points with values less than {@code spillerLimit} when brought into a 0-255
259     * range, and then expanding those points pseudo-randomly while keeping the same value for any expanded range as its
260     * original point.
261     * @param width the width of the 2D array to return
262     * @param height the height of the 2D array to return
263     * @param spillerLimit the upper exclusive bound for the values that will be present in toFill when this finishes
264     * @param rng any IRNG to generate random values during expansion, such as {@link RNG} or {@link GWTRNG}
265     * @return a 2D int array containing ints from 0 (inclusive) to {@code spillerLimit} (exclusive)
266     */
267    public static int[][] blueSpill(int width, int height, int spillerLimit, IRNG rng) {
268        return blueSpill(new int[width][height], spillerLimit, rng);
269    }

271    /**
272     * Modifies {@code toFill} in-place by filling it with the (seeded variant) blue noise of this class, finding any
273     * points with values less than {@code spillerLimit} when brought into a 0-255 range, and then expanding those
274     * points pseudo-randomly while keeping the same value for any expanded range as its original point.
275     * @param toFill a 2D int array that will be modified in-place and entirely replaced; its contents don't matter
276     * @param spillerLimit the upper exclusive bound for the values that will be present in toFill when this finishes
277     * @param rng any IRNG to generate random values during expansion, such as {@link RNG} or {@link GWTRNG}
278     * @return {@code toFill}, after modifications
279     */
280    public static int[][] blueSpill(int[][] toFill, int spillerLimit, IRNG rng) {
281        final int width = toFill.length, height = toFill[0].length,
282                xOffset = rng.next(5) + rng.next(5) + 1, yOffset = rng.next(5) + rng.next(5) + 1,
283                seed0 = rng.nextInt(), seed1 = rng.nextInt();//, noiseChoice = rng.next(6);
284//        final byte[] c0 = ALT_NOISE[noiseChoice], c1 = ALT_NOISE[noiseChoice ^ (rng.next(6)|1)];
285        final Direction[] dirs = Direction.CARDINALS;
286        Direction d;
287        int t, rx, ry, ctr;
288        for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
289            for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
290                toFill[x][y] = (getSeededSeamless(x + xOffset, y, seed0) + getSeededSeamless(x, y + yOffset, seed1) + 256) >> 1;
291            }
292        }
293        int[] ox = new int[width], oy = new int[height];
294        boolean anySuccesses = false;
295        do {
296            ctr = 0;
297            rng.randomOrdering(width, ox);
298            rng.randomOrdering(height, oy);
299            for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
300                rx = ox[x];
301                for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
302                    ry = oy[y];
303                    if ((t = toFill[rx][ry]) < spillerLimit) {
304                        d = dirs[rng.next(2)];
305                        if (rx + d.deltaX >= 0 && rx + d.deltaX < width && ry + d.deltaY >= 0 && ry + d.deltaY < height &&
306                                toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] >= spillerLimit) {
307                            toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] = t;
308                            ctr++;
309                        }
310                        d = dirs[rng.next(2)];
311                        if (rx + d.deltaX >= 0 && rx + d.deltaX < width && ry + d.deltaY >= 0 && ry + d.deltaY < height &&
312                                toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] >= spillerLimit) {
313                            toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] = t;
314                            ctr++;
315                        }
316                    }
317
318                }
319            }
320            if(!anySuccesses && ctr == 0)
321            {
322                ArrayTools.fill(toFill, 0);
323                return toFill;
324            }
325            else 
326                anySuccesses = true;
327        } while (ctr > 0);
328        do {
329            ctr = 0;
330            rng.randomOrdering(width, ox);
331            rng.randomOrdering(height, oy);
332            for (int x = 0; x < width; x++) {
333                rx = ox[x];
334                for (int y = 0; y < height; y++) {
335                    ry = oy[y];
336                    if ((t = toFill[rx][ry]) < spillerLimit) {
337                        for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
338                            d = dirs[i];
339                            if (rx + d.deltaX >= 0 && rx + d.deltaX < width && ry + d.deltaY >= 0 && ry + d.deltaY < height &&
340                                    toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] >= spillerLimit) {
341                                toFill[rx + d.deltaX][ry + d.deltaY] = t;
342                                ctr++;
343                            }
344                        }
345                    }
346
347                }
348            }
349        } while (ctr > 0);
350        return toFill;
351    }
